  <subsection xml:id="subsec-transformations-other-trig-functions">
    <title>Graphing Transformations of Other Trigonometric Functions</title>
    <p>
      Similar to the graphs of sine and cosine, the graphs of the other trigonometric functions can undergo vertical stretching and compressing, horizontal stretching and compressing, phase shift, and vertical shift transformations. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Talk about Vertical Stretch/Compression
    </p>
    <p>
      Functions of the form
      <me>y=A\tan(x)\quad y=A\cot(x)\quad y=A\csc(x)\quad y=A\sec(x)</me>
      undergo a Vertical Stretch or Compression. If <m>|A| \gt 1</m>, it's a stretch; if <m>0 \lt |A| \lt 1</m>, it's a compression.
    </p>
    <remark>
      <title>Transformations of the Tangent and Cotangent Functions</title>
      <p>
        Tangent and cotangent functions of the form 
        <me>y=A\cdot\tan(B(x-C))+D \mbox{ and } y=A\cdot\cot(B(x-C))+D</me> 
        undergo the following transformations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Stretching/compressing factor: <m>|A|</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Period: <m>\frac{\pi}{|B|}</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Phase Shift: <m>C</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Vertical Shift: <m>D</m></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    
      <p>
        The tangent function has vertical asymptotes at
        <me>x=C+\frac{\pi}{|B|}n</me>,
        and the cotangent function has vertical asymptotes at
        <me>x=C+\frac{\pi}{2|B|}n</me>,
        where <m>n</m> is an integer.
      </p>
    
      <p>
        Tangent and cotangent functions of the form
        <me>y=A\cdot\tan(Bx-E)+D \quad y=A\cdot\cot(Bx-E)+D</me>
        undergo the following transformations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Stretching/compressing factor: <m>|A|</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Period: <m>\frac{\pi}{|B|}</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Phase Shift: <m>\frac{E}{B}</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Vertical Shift: <m>D</m></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    
      <p>
        The tangent function has vertical asymptotes at
        <me>x=\frac{E}{B}+\frac{\pi}{|B|}n</me>,
        and the cotangent function has vertical asymptotes at
        <me>x=\frac{E}{B}+\frac{\pi}{2|B|}n</me>,
        where <m>n</m> is an integer.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Give an example that involes a few of these transformations
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Vertical Stretch/Compression:</b>
      If <m>y = A \tan(x)</m>, where <m>A</m> is a constant, it results in a vertical stretch or compression.
      If <m>|A| \gt 1</m>, it's a stretch; if <m>0 \lt |A| \lt 1</m>, it's a compression.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Vertical Shift:</b>
      For <m>y = \tan(x) + D</m>, the graph is vertically shifted up or down by <m>D</m> units.
      Positive <m>D</m> shifts upward, and negative <m>D</m> shifts downward.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Horizontal Stretch/Compression:</b>
      If <m>y = \tan(Bx)</m>, where <m>B</m> is a constant, it causes a horizontal stretch or compression.
      If <m>|B| \gt 1</m>, it's a compression; if <m>0 \lt |B| \lt 1</m>, it's a stretch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Horizontal Shift:</b>
      For <m>y = \tan(x - C)</m>, the graph is horizontally shifted right or left by <m>C</m> units.
      Positive <m>C</m> shifts to the right, and negative <m>C</m> shifts to the left.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Reflection:</b>
      Adding a negative sign outside the function, <m>y = -\tan(x)</m>, reflects the graph across the x-axis.
      If the negative sign is inside, <m>y = \tan(-x)</m>, it reflects across the y-axis.
    </p> 
    <p>
      The transformations for cotangent, cosecant, and secant are similar to those of tangent, with corresponding changes in the vertical stretch/compression, vertical shift, horizontal stretch/compression, horizontal shift, and reflection.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let's sum up all of the transformations into one equation for tan/cot/csc/sec.
    </p>
